transcripts.transcript: Hello and welcome to my course, Vault Tokens for Vault Associate Version 003. I'm Ned Bellevvan, a HasyCorp ambassador and certified HasyCorp instructor. And in this course, we are going to examine a fundamental component of the Vault architecture, tokens. This course is part of a series of courses meant to prepare you for the Vault associate exam, specifically version 003 of the exam. The exam is broken up into 9 high-level objectives that you're seeing right now. Each high-level objective is broken up into enabling objectives. The high-level objective we're covering in this course is vault tokens, and it has 6 enabling objectives. Choose between service and batch tokens based on use case. Describe root token uses and life cycle. Explain the purpose of token accessors. Explain the impact of time to live, or TTL. Explain orphaned tokens, and describe how to create tokens based on need. We will cover each of these objectives in detail throughout the rest of this course, but before we dig into Vault tokens proper, we first need to review Volt's logical architecture to understand the role that tokens play.
